'''Clarence Thomas''' (born June 23, 1948) is an American lawyer and jurist who serves as an [[associate justice of the Supreme Court of the United States]]. He [[Clarence Thomas Supreme Court nomination|was nominated by]] President [[George H. W. Bush]] to succeed [[Thurgood Marshall]] and has served since 1991. After Marshall, Thomas is the second [[African Americans|African American]] to serve on the Supreme Court and has been its longest-serving member since [[Anthony Kennedy]]'s retirement in 2018. Since [[Stephen Breyer]]'s retirement in 2022, he is also the Court's oldest member.

Thomas was born in [[Pin Point, Georgia]]. After his father abandoned the family, he was raised by his grandfather in a poor [[Gullah]] community near [[Savannah, Georgia|Savannah]]. Growing up as a devout Catholic, Thomas originally intended to be a [[priest]] in the [[Catholic Church]] but was frustrated over the church's insufficient attempts to combat racism. He abandoned his aspiration of becoming a [[clergyman]] to attend the [[College of the Holy Cross]] and [[Yale Law School]], where he was influenced by a number of conservative authors, notably [[Thomas Sowell]]. Upon graduating, he was appointed as an [[Missouri Attorney General|assistant attorney general]] in [[Missouri]] and later entered private practice there. He became a [[legislative assistant]] to U.S. Senator [[John Danforth]] in 1979, and was made Assistant Secretary for Civil Rights at the [[United States Department of Education|U.S. Department of Education]] in 1981. President [[Ronald Reagan]] appointed Thomas as Chairman of the [[Equal Employment Opportunity Commission]] (EEOC) the next year.

President George H. W. Bush nominated Thomas to the [[United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit]] in 1990. He served in that role for 19 months before filling Marshall's seat on the Supreme Court. Thomas's confirmation hearings were bitter and intensely fought, centering on an accusation that he had sexually harassed [[Anita Hill]], a subordinate at the [[United States Department of Education|Department of Education]] and the EEOC.{{Sfn|Alexander Jr.|1997|p=378}} Hill alleged that Thomas made multiple inappropriate sexual and romantic overtures to her; Thomas and his supporters alleged that Hill and her political supporters had fabricated the accusation to prevent the appointment of a black conservative. The Senate confirmed Thomas by a vote of 52–48, the narrowest margin in a century.<ref name="Senate.gov">{{cite news |title= Roll Call Vote 102nd Congress - 1st Session |publisher=U.S. Senate |date= October 15, 1991 |url= https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=102&session=1&vote=00220 |access-date= May 19, 2020 |archive-date= April 7, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180407085736/https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=102&session=1&vote=00220 |url-status= live }}</ref>

Since the death of [[Antonin Scalia]], Thomas has been the Court's foremost [[originalism|originalist]], stressing the [[original meaning]] in interpreting the [[Constitution of the United States|Constitution]].{{Sfn|Staab|2022|p=2}} In contrast to Scalia—who had been the only other consistent originalist—he pursues a more [[Classical liberalism|classically liberal]] variety of originalism.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Sandefur |first=Timothy |date=2008-09-22 |title=Clarence Thomas's Jurisprudence Unexplained |url=https://papers.ssrn.com/abstract=1272053 |journal=New York University Journal of Law & Liberty |language=en |location=Rochester, N.Y. |pages=535–556|ssrn=1272053 }}</ref> Thomas was known for his silence during most oral arguments,{{Sfn|Maggs|2017|p=215}} though has since begun asking more questions to counsel.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Severino |first=Carrie |author-link=Carrie Severino |date=2021-08-18 |title=Justice Thomas has made the new oral argument format a winner |url=https://www.scotusblog.com/2021/08/justice-thomas-has-made-the-new-oral-argument-format-a-winner/ |access-date=2022-07-09 |website=[[SCOTUSblog]] |language=en-US}}</ref> He is notable for his majority opinions in ''[[Good News Club v. Milford Central School]]'' (determining the freedom of religious speech in relation to the [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]]) and ''[[New York State Rifle & Pistol Association, Inc. v. Bruen]]'' (affirming the individual [[Right to keep and bear arms|right to bear arms]] outside the home), as well as his dissent in ''[[Gonzales v. Raich]]'' (arguing that Congress may not [[criminalize]] the private cultivation of [[medical marijuana]]). He is widely considered to be the Court's [[Ideological leanings of United States Supreme Court justices|most conservative member]]. 

{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2024}}
==Early life==
Thomas was born on June 23, 1948, in his parents' wooden shack in [[Pin Point, Georgia]].{{sfn|Foskett|2004|p=50}}{{sfn|Mayer|Abramson|1994|p=32–33}} Pin Point was a small community near [[Savannah, Georgia|Savannah]] founded by [[Freedman|freedmen]] in the 1880s.{{sfn|Foskett|2004|p=47}} He was the second of three children of M.C. Thomas, a farm worker, and Leola Williams.{{sfn|Foskett|2004|p=50}} Williams had been born out of wedlock; after her mother's death, she was sent from [[Liberty County, Georgia]], to live with an aunt in Pin Point.{{Sfn|Foskett|2004|p=46}}<ref name="oyez.org">{{cite web |title=Clarence Thomas: Biography |url=https://www.oyez.org/oyez/resource/legal_entity/106/biography |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030513064005/https://www.oyez.org/oyez/resource/legal_entity/106/biography |archive-date=May 13, 2003 |access-date=June 27, 2017 |website=[[Oyez Project]]}}</ref>{{Sfn|Cox|2008|p=12}} The family were descendants of [[Slavery in the United States|enslaved people]] and spoke [[Gullah language|Gullah]] as a [[first language]].<ref name="Gullah">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/12/14/politics/14TWOR.html|title=In His Own Words: Justice Clarence Thomas|newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=December 14, 2000|access-date=March 25, 2010|archive-date=April 3, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120403082027/http://www.nytimes.com/2000/12/14/politics/14TWOR.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Thomas's earliest known ancestors were slaves named Sandy and Peggy, who were born in the late 18th century and owned by wealthy [[Planter class|planter]] Josiah Wilson of Liberty County.{{sfn|Foskett|2004|pp=22–23}} Thomas's older sister, Emma, was born in 1946, and his younger brother, Myers, in 1949.{{sfn|Foskett|2004|pp=50–51}}

Upon becoming pregnant with Thomas's older sister, Leola was expelled from her [[Baptist church]] and dropped out of high school after the 10th grade; her father ordered her to marry M.C. in January 1947. After three years of marriage, M.C. sued for divorce, claiming that Leola neglected the children, and a judge granted the request in March 1951.{{sfn|Foskett|2004|pp=50–51}} After the divorce, M.C. moved to [[Savannah, Georgia|Savannah]] and later Pennsylvania, visiting his children only once. Leola went to work as a maid in Savannah during the week and returned to Pin Point on the weekends. Custody of the children was awarded to Leola's aunt.{{sfn|Foskett|2004|pp=53}}<ref name="emm">{{cite news |last=Tumulty |first=Karen |author-link=Karen Tumulty |date=July 5, 1991 |title=Sister of High Court Nominee Traveled Different Road : Family: Although Clarence Thomas held her up as a horrible example, Emma Mae Martin defends her life and the choices she made. |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1991-07-05-mn-1766-story.html |access-date=October 3, 2023}}</ref> When her aunt's house burned down in 1955, Leola took her children to live with her in the room she rented in a tenement with an outdoor toilet in Savannah, leaving her daughter with the aunt in Pin Point. She asked her father, Myers Anderson, for help. He initially refused but agreed after his wife threatened to throw him out.{{sfn|Mayer|Abramson|1994|p=37}}{{sfn|Merida|Fletcher|2008|p=57}}[[File:1967 Clarence Thomas yearbook portrait (cropped).jpg|thumb|Thomas's 1967 high school yearbook picture<!-- This image has a bigger width to prevent the text wrapping on the new vector. -->|left|263x263px]]Thomas and his brother went to live with Anderson, his maternal grandfather, in 1955 and experienced amenities such as [[Tap water|indoor plumbing]] and regular meals for the first time.{{Sfn|Merida|Fletcher|2008|p=54–55}} Despite having little formal education, Anderson had built a successful business delivering coal, oil, and ice.{{sfn|Mayer|Abramson|1994|p=37}} When racial unrest led to widespread protest and marches in Savannah from 1960 to 1963, Anderson used his wealth to bail out demonstrators and took his grandchildren to meetings promoted by the [[NAACP]].{{Sfn|Foskett|2004|p=54–55}} Thomas has described his grandfather as the person who has influenced his life the most.{{Sfn|Gerber|2002|p=11}} 

Anderson converted to [[Catholicism]] and sent Thomas to be educated at a series of Catholic schools. Thomas attended the predominantly black St. Pius X High School in [[Chatham County, Georgia|Chatham County]]<ref>{{Cite web |date=February 16, 2022 |title=Historical Marker Dedication: St. Pius X High School |url=https://georgiahistory.com/events/historical-marker-dedication-st-pius-x-high-school/ |access-date=June 11, 2023 |website=Georgia Historical Society |language=en-US |archive-date=December 6, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221206194037/https://georgiahistory.com/events/historical-marker-dedication-st-pius-x-high-school/ |url-status=dead }}</ref> for two years before transferring to St. John Vianney's Minor Seminary on the [[Isle of Hope, Georgia|Isle of Hope]], where he was the segregated [[boarding school]]'s first black student.<ref name="businessweek">{{cite web |last=Brady |first=Diane |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2007-03-11/online-extra-supreme-court-justice-clarence-thomas-speaks |title=Supreme Court Justice Clarence Thomas Speaks |work=[[Bloomberg BusinessWeek]]|publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]]|location=New York City |date=March 12, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070312181418/http://www.businessweek.com/magazine/content/07_11/b4025080.htm |archive-date=March 12, 2007 |access-date=July 27, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=July 2, 1991 |title=Supreme Court Nominee's Story Classic of Success |url=https://www.oklahoman.com/story/news/1991/07/02/supreme-court-nominees-story-classic-of-success/62523628007/ |access-date=June 11, 2023 |website=[[The Oklahoman]] |language=en-US}}</ref> Though he experienced [[hazing]], he performed well academically.<ref name="oyez.org" /> He spent many hours at the [[East Henry Street Carnegie Library|Carnegie Library]], the only library for Blacks in Savannah before libraries were desegregated in 1961.{{Sfn|Merida|Fletcher|2008|p=53}}<ref name="alger">{{cite news |last1=VanSickle |first1=Abbie |last2=Eder |first2=Steve |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/09/us/clarence-thomas-horatio-alger-association.html |title=Where Clarence Thomas Entered an Elite Circle and Opened a Door to the Court |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=July 12, 2023 |access-date=October 6, 2023}}</ref>{{Refn|In 2001, a wing was restored with funds donated by Thomas's friends [[Harlan Crow]] and [[Wayne Huizenga]] and, despite public protests, named after Thomas.{{Sfn|Merida|Fletcher|2008|p=54}}<ref name="alger"/>|group=lower-alpha}}

When Thomas was ten years old, Anderson began putting his grandsons to work during the summers, helping him build a house on a plot of farmland he owned, building fences, and doing farm work.{{sfn|Foskett|2004|p=10–11}} He believed in hard work and self-reliance,{{sfn|Foskett|2004|p=12}} never showed his grandsons affection,{{sfn|Foskett|2004|p=10–11}} beat them frequently according to Leola, and impressed the importance of a good education on them.{{sfn|Mayer|Abramson|1994|p=38–39}} Anderson taught Thomas that "all of our rights as human beings came from God, not man", and that [[Racial segregation in the United States|racial segregation]] was a violation of [[divine law]].{{Sfn|Staab|2022|p=126–127}} 

=== Education ===

During his freshman year from 1967 to 1968, Thomas attended [[Conception Abbey|Conception Seminary College]], a [[Benedictines|Benedictine]] seminary in [[Missouri]], with the intent to become a priest; no one in Thomas's family had attended college before.{{sfn|Foskett|2004|p=88–91}}<ref name="businessweek" /> After [[Martin Luther King, Jr.'s assassination|Martin Luther King Jr.'s assassination]], he overheard a fellow student say, "Good. I hope the son of a bitch dies" and "[t]hat's what they should do to all the niggers".{{sfn|Foskett|2004|p=91}}<ref name="businessweek2">{{cite news |last=Brady |first=Diane |date=March 11, 2007 |title=The Holy Cross Fraternity |work=[[Bloomberg BusinessWeek]] |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/bw/stories/2007-03-11/the-holy-cross-fraternity |url-status=live |access-date=February 29, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200820182426/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2007-03-11/the-holy-cross-fraternity |archive-date=August 20, 2020}}</ref><ref name="nytimes">{{cite news |title=Judge Portrayed as a Product Of Ideals Clashing With Life |first=David |last=Margolick |author-link=David Margolick |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=July 3, 1991 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/07/03/us/judge-portrayed-as-a-product-of-ideals-clashing-with-life.html |access-date=October 19, 2008 |archive-date=June 19, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120619233811/http://www.nytimes.com/1991/07/03/us/judge-portrayed-as-a-product-of-ideals-clashing-with-life.html |url-status=live }}</ref> The display of racism moved Thomas to leave the seminary.{{Sfn|Gerber|2002|p=12}} He thought the church did not do enough to combat racism and resolved to abandon the priesthood.{{Sfn|Brady|2012|p=10}}{{sfn|Foskett|2004|p=91}} He left at the end of the semester.{{sfn|Foskett|2004|p=91}} 

At a nun's suggestion, Thomas enrolled at the [[College of the Holy Cross]], an elite Catholic college in [[Massachusetts]], as a sophomore transfer student on a full academic scholarship.<ref>{{Harvnb|Foskett|2004|p=95–97}}; {{Harvnb|Merida|Fletcher|2008|p=102–103}}</ref><ref name="nyt060609ct">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/07/us/politics/07affirm.html|title=For Sotomayor and Thomas, Paths Diverge at Race|first1=Jodi|last1=Kantor|author-link1=Jodi Kantor|first2=David|last2=Gonzalez|author-link2=David Gonzalez (journalist)|newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=June 6, 2009|access-date=June 7, 2009|archive-date=March 6, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140306073526/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/07/us/politics/07affirm.html|url-status=live}}</ref> He was one of the college's first black students, being one of 20 recruited by President [[John E. Brooks]] in 1968 in a group that also included future attorney [[Ted Wells]], running back [[Ed Jenkins (American football)|Eddie Jenkins, Jr.]], and novelist [[Edward P. Jones]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Brady |first=Diane |title=How This Holy Cross Leader Helped Clarence Thomas And Ted Wells |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/dianebrady/2023/01/17/to-be-an-ally-learn-from-the-man-who-helped-clarence-thomas/ |date=January 17, 2023 |access-date=October 8, 2023 |work=[[Forbes]]}}</ref> In the fall of that year, Thomas and other black students founded the college's [[Black Student Union]] (BSU), which became an important part of their campus identity.<ref>{{Harvnb|Foskett|2004|p=99}}; {{Harvnb|Gerber|2002|p=12}}</ref> Without financial support from his grandfather, he defrayed his expenses by working as a waiter and dishwasher in the college's dining hall.<ref>{{Harvnb|Merida|Fletcher|2008|p=105}}; {{Harvnb|Foskett|2004|p=97}}</ref> Thomas later recalled, "I was 19. My only hope was Holy Cross College".<ref name=":8">{{Cite web |last=Reis |first=Jacqueline |date=January 26, 2012 |title=Clarence Thomas honored at Holy Cross |url=https://www.telegram.com/story/news/local/north/2012/01/27/clarence-thomas-honored-at-holy/49755411007/ |access-date=May 27, 2023 |website=[[Telegram & Gazette]] |language=en-US}}</ref>

Professors at Holy Cross remembered Thomas as a determined, diligent student.{{Sfn|Merida|Fletcher|2008|p=104–105}} He kept to a strict routine of studying alone and stayed back during holidays to continue working.{{Sfn|Mayer|Abramson|1994–1995|p=96}} Thomas C. Lawler, an English professor at Holy Cross,<ref>{{Cite web |title=Obituaries {{!}} Thomas C. Lawler |url=https://telegram.com/obituaries/pneo0259365 |access-date=June 28, 2023 |website=[[Telegram & Gazette]] |language=en}}</ref> recalled him as having "never talked very much in class. He was the kind of person you really might not notice".{{Sfn|Merida|Fletcher|2008|p=104–105}} By contrast, he was outspoken at BSU meetings, distinguishing himself as a contrarian who often feuded with Ted Wells. Future NFL running back [[Ed Jenkins (American football)|Ed Jenkins]], a BSU member, said Thomas "could turn on a dime and reduce you to intellectual rubble".{{Sfn|Merida|Fletcher|2008|p=110–111}}{{Sfn|Foskett|2004|p=99–100}} Edward P. Jones, who lived across from Thomas as a sophomore, reflected that "there was a fierce determination I sensed from him [Thomas], that he was going to get as much as he could and get as far, ultimately, as he could".<ref name="nyt-thomas" /> [[File:HC Dinand Library 1.'23.jpg|thumb|267x267px|Dinand Library at the [[College of the Holy Cross]], where Thomas studied for college{{Sfn|Brady|2012|p=92, 94}}]]

Thomas became a vocal student activist as an undergraduate. He became acquainted with [[Black separatism]], the [[Black Muslim Movement]], the [[Black power movement]], and displayed a poster of [[Malcolm X]] in his dormitory room.{{sfn|Mayer|Abramson|1994|p=51}} When some black students were disproportionately punished in comparison with white students for the same violation, he suggested a walkout in protest. The BSU adopted his idea, and Thomas, along with 60 other black students, departed campus.{{Sfn|Cox|2008|p=43–44}}{{sfn|Robin|2019|p=30}} Some of the priests negotiated with the protesting black students to reenter the school.<ref name="businessweek" /> When administrators granted amnesty to all protesters, Thomas returned to the college, later also to attend [[Opposition to United States involvement in the Vietnam War|anti-war marches]]. In April 1970, he participated in the violent [[Harvard University and the Vietnam War#1970: Harvard Square riots|1970 Harvard Square riots]].{{Sfn|Cox|2008|p=44–45}} He has credited his protests for his turn toward conservatism and subsequent disillusionment with leftist movements.{{Sfn|Cox|2008|p=44}}<ref name="tahnba">{{cite web |work=teachingamericanhistory.org |title=Speech to the National Bar Association |first=Clarence |last=Thomas |date=July 28, 1998 |url=https://teachingamericanhistory.org/document/speech-to-the-national-bar-association-2/ |access-date=February 22, 2022}}</ref><ref name="nyt-thomas">{{cite news |last1=Hakim |first1=Danny |last2=Becker |first2=Jo |date=February 22, 2022 |title=The Long Crusade of Clarence and Ginni Thomas |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2022/02/22/magazine/clarence-thomas-ginni-thomas.html |url-status=live |url-access=subscription |access-date=February 22, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220222123822/https://www.nytimes.com/2022/02/22/magazine/clarence-thomas-ginni-thomas.html |archive-date=February 22, 2022}}</ref>

Having struggled with English as a native speaker of [[Gullah language|Gullah]], Thomas chose to major in [[English studies|English literature]].{{Sfn|Merida|Fletcher|2008|p=105}}<ref name="Sotomayor and Thomas">{{Cite news |last1=Kantor |first1=Jodi |author-link1=Jodi Kantor |last2=Gonzalez |first2=David |author-link2=David Gonzalez (journalist) |date=June 6, 2009 |title=For Sotomayor and Thomas, Paths Diverge at Race |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/07/us/politics/07affirm.html |url-status=live |access-date=April 5, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201206220724/https://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/07/us/politics/07affirm.html |archive-date=December 6, 2020}}</ref> He became a member of [[Alpha Sigma Nu]], the Jesuit [[honor society]], and the Purple Key Society, of which he was the only black member.{{Sfn|Merida|Fletcher|2008|p=112}} The college's focus on a [[liberal arts education]] introduced him to the writings of black intellectuals such as [[Richard Wright (author)|Richard Wright]], whose literary works Thomas sympathized with.{{Sfn|Mayer|Abramson|1994|p=51}} He also admired Malcolm X and recalled reading ''[[The Autobiography of Malcolm X]]'' to the point of wearing down the pages of his copy.<ref name="abc news">{{Cite news |author=Greenburg, Jan Crawford |author-link=Jan Crawford Greenburg |date=September 30, 2007 |title=Clarence Thomas: A Silent Justice Speaks Out |work=[[ABC News]] |url=https://abcnews.go.com/TheLaw/story?id=3664944&page=1 |url-status=live |access-date=October 18, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080919015232/http://www.abcnews.go.com/TheLaw/story?id=3664944&page=1 |archive-date=September 19, 2008}}</ref>

Thomas graduated on June 4, 1971, with a [[Bachelor of Arts]], ''[[Latin honors|cum laude]]'', ranked ninth in his class.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mayer|Abramson|1994|p=52}}; {{Harvnb|Foskett|2004|p=116}}.</ref> He applied to and was accepted by [[Yale Law School]], [[Harvard Law School]], and the [[University of Pennsylvania Law School]].{{Sfn|Brady|2012|p=184}}<ref>{{Cite web |last=Arnsdorf |first=Isaac |date=October 11, 2007 |title=In new book, Clarence Thomas directs ire toward Yale Law |url=https://yaledailynews.com/blog/2007/10/11/in-new-book-clarence-thomas-directs-ire-toward-yale-law/ |access-date=January 20, 2024 |website=[[Yale Daily News]] |language=en}}</ref> That same year, Thomas matriculated at [[Yale Law School]] as one of 12 black students.{{sfn|Mayer|Abramson|1994|p=58}} Yale offered him the best financial aid package, and he was attracted to the civil rights activism of some of its faculty members.{{sfn|Foskett|2004|p=118–121}}{{Sfn|Thomas|2002|p=106}} Finding it difficult to keep up with the school's expectations, he struggled to connect with other students who came from upper-class backgrounds. He enrolled in the most difficult courses and became a student of property law scholar [[Quintin Johnstone]], who became his favorite professor.{{Sfn|Foskett|2004|p=122–125}}{{sfn|Cox|2008|p=47–48}} Johnstone remembered Thomas as having "performed very well".{{Sfn|Thomas|2002|p=107}} [[Guido Calabresi]], the [[dean of Yale Law School]], described Thomas and fellow student [[Hillary Clinton]] as "both excellent students [who] had the same kind of reputation".{{Sfn|Thomas|2002|p=107}} 

Thomas obtained his [[Juris Doctor]] on May 20, 1974.{{Sfn|Cox|2008|p=50}} After graduation, he sought to enter private practice as a corporate lawyer in [[Atlanta Georgia|Atlanta, Georgia]].{{Sfn|Foskett|2004|p=129–131}} He saw his experience in law school as disappointing, as law firms assumed he was accepted because of [[affirmative action in the United States|affirmative action]].{{Sfn|Brady|2012|p=217}} According to Thomas, the law firms also "asked pointed questions, unsubtly suggesting that they doubted I was as smart as my grades indicated".<ref name="newsweek">{{cite magazine|first=Dahlia|last=Lithwick|author-link=Dahlia Lithwick|url=http://www.newsweek.com/id/161228|title=From Clarence Thomas to Palin|magazine=[[Newsweek]]|location=New York City|date=September 27, 2008|access-date=October 18, 2008|archive-date=October 13, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081013184559/http://www.newsweek.com/id/161228|url-status=live}}</ref> In his 2007 memoir, he wrote: "I peeled a fifteen-cent sticker off a package of cigars and stuck it on the frame of my law degree to remind myself of the mistake I'd made by going to Yale. I never did change my mind about its value."{{sfn|Thomas|2007|pp=143–44}} Hill, Jones, and Farrington, the Savannah law firm where Thomas had interned the previous summer, offered him a job upon graduation, but he declined.{{sfn|Thomas|2002|p=113}}{{Sfn|Mayer|Abramson|1994–1995|p=100}}

== Early legal career ==
[[File:441-G-81-136-10 Bell Swears in Clarence Thomas (cropped).jpg|thumb|236x236px|Thomas is sworn in as Assistant Secretary of Education for the [[Office for Civil Rights]] in 1981]]
With no job offers from major law firms, Thomas took a position as an associate with Missouri attorney general [[John Danforth]], who offered him the prospect of practicing what he liked.{{sfn|Foskett|2004|p=131–133}} Thomas moved to [[Saint Louis Missouri|Saint Louis]] to study for [[The Missouri Bar|the Missouri bar]], and was admitted on September 13, 1974.{{sfn|Foskett|2004|p=134, 139}} He remained financially destitute even after leaving Yale, trying unsuccessfully on one occasion to make money by selling his blood at a [[blood bank]], and hoped that by working for Danforth he might later acquire a job in private practice.{{sfn|Cox|2008|p=51}}{{sfn|Foskett|2004|p=129, 140}}

From 1974 to 1977, Thomas was an assistant attorney general of Missouri—the only African-American member of Danforth's staff. He worked first in the office's criminal appeals division and later in the revenue and taxation division. Thomas conducted lawsuits independently, gaining a reputation as a fair but controversial prosecutor.{{sfn|Foskett|2004|pp=138–141}} Years later, after he joined the Supreme Court, Thomas recalled his position in Missouri as "the best job I've ever had".{{sfn|Foskett|2004|p=147}}

When Danforth was elected to the U.S. Senate in 1976, Thomas left to become an attorney in [[Monsanto]]'s legal department in Saint Louis.{{sfn|Foskett|2004|p=146–147}} He found the job unsatisfying, so left to rejoin Danforth in [[Washington, D.C.]], as a legislative assistant.{{sfn|Foskett|2004|p=149}} From 1979 to 1981, he handled energy issues for the [[United States Senate Committee on Commerce, Science, and Transportation|Senate Commerce Committee]]. Thomas, who had switched his party affiliation from Democratic to Republican while working for Danforth in Missouri,{{Sfn|Herman|Friedman|Israel|2013|p=386}} soon drew the attention of officials in the newly elected [[Reagan Administration]] as a [[Black conservatism in the United States|Black conservative]].{{Sfn|Herman|Friedman|Israel|2013|p=386}}{{sfn|Foskett|2004|p=149–150}} Pendleton James, Reagan's personnel director, offered Thomas the position of assistant secretary for civil rights at the [[U.S. Department of Education,|U.S. Department of Education]]. Initially reluctant, Thomas agreed after Danforth and others pressed him to take the post.{{sfn|Foskett|2004|p=153–156}}[[File:441-G-81-121-3 Clarence Thomas, Assistant Secretary for Civil Rights, in His Office, May 18, 1981 (cropped).jpg|left|thumb|259x259px|Thomas in his office on May 18, 1981]]President [[Ronald Reagan]] nominated Thomas as assistant secretary of education for the [[Office for Civil Rights]] (OCR) on May 1, 1981.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nomination of Clarence Thomas To Be an Assistant Secretary of Education {{pipe}} The American Presidency Project |url=https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/nomination-clarence-thomas-be-assistant-secretary-education |website=presidency.ucsb.edu |access-date=March 26, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220326193047/https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/nomination-clarence-thomas-be-assistant-secretary-education |archive-date=March 26, 2022 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Weekly Compilation of Presidential Documents |date=1981 |publisher=[[Office of the Federal Register]] |page=488 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R88P6TH4Oc4C&q=clarence+thomas |access-date=March 26, 2022}}</ref> The Senate received the nomination on May 28, 1981, and Thomas was quickly confirmed before the [[Senate Labor and Human Resources Committee]] on June 19, succeeding Cynthia Brown at the age of 32.{{sfn|Foskett|2004|p=156}}<ref>{{cite web |title=PN315 — Clarence Thomas — Department of Education |url=https://www.congress.gov/nomination/97th-congress/315 |website=[[Congress.gov]] |date=June 26, 1981 |access-date=March 26, 2022}}</ref> He held the position for a brief period before James offered him a new position as chairman of the [[Equal Employment Opportunity Commission]] (EEOC), a promotion that Thomas believed, as with his position in the OCR, was because of his race.{{sfn|Cox|2008|p=54}} After James consulted the President, Thomas hesitantly took up the chair with Reagan's approval.{{sfn|Foskett|2004|p=159}}

Thomas chaired the [[Equal Employment Opportunity Commission]] (EEOC) from 1982 to 1990. As chairman, he was tasked with enforcing the [[Civil Rights Act of 1964]] in an agency that had been mutually resented by both Democrats and Republicans. He announced a reorganization of the EEOC and upgraded its record-keeping under an uncompromising leadership that eschewed racial quotas.{{sfn|Cox|2008|p=54}}{{sfn|Foskett|2004|p=160–161, 177}} Concerned by the EEOC's limited statutory authority, Thomas sought to impose criminal penalties for employers who practiced [[employment discrimination]], moving to shift funding towards agency investigators. Though he had been critical of [[Affirmative action in the United States|affirmative action]], Thomas also opposed the Reagan Administration's agenda to remove affirmative action policies, believing it to be a detraction from socioeconomic issues.{{sfn|Foskett|2004|p=153, 172–175}}{{Sfn|Herman|Friedman|Israel|2013|p=386}}

During Thomas's tenure, he was credited with improving the efficiency of the EEOC.{{Sfn|Gerber|2002|p=13}} Settlement award amounts to victims of discrimination tripled, while the number of suits filed decreased. The EEOC's lack of the use of goals and timetables drew criticism from civil rights advocates, who lobbied representatives to review the EEOC's practices; Thomas testified before Congress more than 50 times. Near the end of his final term, the EEOC came under congressional scrutiny for the mishandling of age-discrimination cases.{{sfn|Foskett|2004|p=177–178, 200–201}}{{Sfn|Herman|Friedman|Israel|2013|p=386–387}}

== District of Columbia Court of Appeals ==
[[File:Ronald Reagan and Clarence Thomas in 1986.jpg|thumb|Thomas with President [[Ronald Reagan]] in 1986, while serving as chairman of the [[Equal Employment Opportunity Commission]]|227x227px]]In early 1989, President [[George H. W. Bush]] expressed interest in nominating Thomas to a federal judgeship. Thomas, now at age 41, initially rejected the position, believing himself unready to make a lifetime commitment to being a judge. White House Counsel [[C. Boyden Gray]] and White House Chief of Staff [[John H. Sununu]] advocated for his nomination, and Judge [[Laurence Silberman]] advised Thomas to accept an appointment.{{sfn|Foskett|2004|p=206–207}} Anticipating Thomas's nomination, a liberal coalition—including the [[Alliance for Justice]] and the [[National Organization for Women]] (NOW)—emerged to oppose his candidacy.{{sfn|Foskett|2004|p=208}}

On October 30, 1989, President [[George H. W. Bush]] nominated Thomas to the [[United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit]] to fill the seat vacated by [[Robert Bork]].{{Sfn|Herman|Friedman|Israel|2013|p=387}}<ref name=":9">[http://www.fjc.gov/servlet/nGetInfo?jid=2362 Profile] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120118025604/http://www.fjc.gov/servlet/nGetInfo?jid=2362|date=January 18, 2012}} at the [[Biographical Directory of Federal Judges]], a [[Public domain]] publication of the [[Federal Judicial Center]]. Retrieved November 1, 2011.</ref> Thomas gained the support of other African American officials, including former transportation secretary [[William Thaddeus Coleman Jr.|William Coleman]], and said that when meeting white [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] staffers in the [[United States Senate]], he was "struck by how easy it had become for sanctimonious whites to accuse a black man of not caring about civil rights".<ref name="abc news" />

In February 1990, the [[Senate Judiciary Committee]] recommended Thomas by a vote of 12 to 1. On March 6, 1990, the Senate confirmed him to the Court of Appeals by a vote of 98 to 2.{{Sfn|Foskett|2004|p=208}} He developed cordial relationships during his 19 months on the federal court, including with Judge [[Ruth Bader Ginsburg]].<ref name="abc news" /> During his judgeship, Thomas authored 19 opinions.{{Sfn|Cox|2008|p=59}}

== Nomination to the Supreme Court ==
{{Main|Clarence Thomas Supreme Court nomination}}
[[File:Thurgood-marshall-2.jpg|thumb|Thomas was nominated to replace Justice [[Thurgood Marshall]] (''pictured''), who announced his retirement on June 27, 1991, due to ill health.{{Sfn|Foskett|2004|p=257–258}}{{Sfn|Greenburg|2007|p=112}}|302x302px]]

When Justice [[William J. Brennan Jr.|William Brennan]] retired from the Supreme Court in July 1990, Thomas was Bush's favorite among the five candidates on his shortlist for the position. However, Bush's advisors, including Attorney General [[Dick Thornburgh]], considered Thomas inexperienced,{{Sfn|Foskett|2004|p=209}} and he instead nominated [[David Souter]] of the [[United States Court of Appeals for the First Circuit|First Circuit Court of Appeals]].<ref name="abc news" /> A year later, Justice [[Thurgood Marshall]] announced his retirement on June 27, 1991, and Bush nominated Thomas to replace him.<ref>[[Maureen Dowd|Dowd, Maureen]]. [https://www.nytimes.com/1991/07/02/us/supreme-court-conservative-black-judge-clarence-thomas-named-marshall-s-court.html "The Supreme Court; Conservative Black Judge, Clarence Thomas, Is Named to Marshall's Court Seat"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090531012158/http://www.nytimes.com/1991/07/02/us/supreme-court-conservative-black-judge-clarence-thomas-named-marshall-s-court.html |date=May 31, 2009 }}, ''[[The New York Times]]'' (July 2, 1991).</ref>{{Sfn|Foskett|2004|p=210}} Bush announced his selection on July 1, calling Thomas the "best qualified at this time".<ref name="abc news" /> Thornburgh cautioned Bush that replacing Marshall with any candidate who was not perceived to share Marshall's views would make confirmation difficult.{{Sfn|Merida|Fletcher|2008|p=172}} 

Liberal interest groups sought to challenge Thomas's nomination by paralleling the same strategy used against Robert Bork's confirmation.{{Sfn|Tushnet|2005|p=335–336}} Abortion-rights groups, including the [[National Abortion Rights Action League]] and the NOW, were concerned that Thomas would be among those to overrule ''[[Roe v. Wade]]''.{{Sfn|Foskett|2004|p=214–215}} Republican officials in turn emphasized his personal history and gathered support from African American interest groups, including the [[NAACP]].{{Sfn|Tushnet|2005|p=336}} Other civil rights organizations, such as the [[Southern Christian Leadership Conference]] and the [[National Urban League]], were convinced not to oppose Thomas, believing that he was Bush's last black nominee. On July 31, 1991, the board of directors of the NAACP voted against endorsing Thomas, announcing their opposition to his confirmation the same day.{{Sfn|Foskett|2004|p=222–223}}

The [[American Bar Association]] (ABA) appraised Thomas as "qualified" for the Supreme Court.{{Sfn|Foskett|2004|p=224}}{{Refn|U.S. presidents have traditionally submitted potential federal court nominees to the [[American Bar Association]] (ABA) for a [[Standing Committee on the Federal Judiciary|confidential rating]] of their judicial temperament, competence and integrity on a three-level scale of well qualified, qualified or unqualified.<ref name="hall">{{cite book|first1=Kermit|last1=Hall|first2=Kevin|last2=McGuire|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8ZvEVHqK17IC&pg=PA155|title=The Judicial Branch|page=155|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|location=Oxford, England|date=2006|isbn=978-0-19-517172-3|access-date=February 19, 2016|archive-date=January 12, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210112051658/https://books.google.com/books?id=8ZvEVHqK17IC&pg=PA155|url-status=live}}</ref>|group=lower-alpha}} The result came in contrast to the "well qualified" rating some nominees had received previously.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jackson |first=Robert L. |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1991-08-28-mn-1149-story.html |title=Thomas Rated 'Qualified' for Court by ABA |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=August 28, 1991 |access-date=November 22, 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Lewis |first=Neil A. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/08/28/us/bar-association-splits-on-fitness-of-thomas-for-the-supreme-court.html |title=Bar Association Splits on Fitness Of Thomas for the Supreme Court |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=August 28, 1991 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150525232314/https://www.nytimes.com/1991/08/28/us/bar-association-splits-on-fitness-of-thomas-for-the-supreme- |archive-date=May 25, 2015 |access-date=November 22, 2023}}</ref> The Bush Administration anticipated that the organization would rate Thomas more poorly than it thought he deserved, so pressured the ABA for at least the mid-level qualified rating while simultaneously discrediting it as partisan.{{Sfn|Viera|Gross|1998|p=137}} Opponents of Thomas's nomination saw the assessment as indicating that he was unfit for the Court.{{Sfn|Foskett|2004|p=225}} The ABA gave Thomas its highest rankings in integrity and judicial temperament and a middle-grade in professional competence.{{Sfn|Foskett|2004|p=224–225}}

On September 10, 1991, formal confirmation hearings began before the Senate Judiciary Committee.{{sfn|Toobin|2007|p=30}}{{Sfn|Cox|2008|p=66}} Thomas testified for 25 hours, the second-longest of any Supreme Court nominee.{{Sfn|Foskett|2004|p=229}} He was reticent when answering senators' questions, recalling what had happened to [[Robert Bork]] when Bork expounded on his judicial philosophy [[Robert Bork Supreme Court nomination|during his confirmation hearings]] four years earlier.{{sfn|Toobin|2007|pp=25, 31}} As many of his earlier writings frequently referenced [[natural law]], his views on the legal theory became a focus of the hearings. Thomas said he regarded natural law as a "philosophical background" to the Constitution.{{sfn|Toobin|2007|p=31}}<ref name="newsweek-natural-law">{{Cite news | work = [[Newsweek]] | location = New York City | title = Natural Law, An Elusive Tradition | first = Kenneth | last = Woodward | date = September 23, 1991 | access-date = April 20, 2009 | url = http://www.newsweek.com/1991/09/22/natural-law-an-elusive-tradition.html | archive-date = June 5, 2014 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140605051815/http://www.newsweek.com/1991/09/22/natural-law-an-elusive-tradition.html | url-status = live }}</ref><ref name="seattle-times-natural-law">{{Cite news | work = [[The Seattle Times]] | date = August 30, 1991 | access-date = April 20, 2009 | first = Aaron | last = Epstein | title = The Natural Law According To Clarence Thomas | url = http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19910830&slug=1302739 | archive-date = September 29, 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120929124817/http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19910830&slug=1302739 | url-status = live }}</ref> 

Ninety witnesses testified in favor of or against Thomas.{{Sfn|Cox|2008|p=70}}{{citation needed|date=November 2023|reason=reliable secondary source needed, cited source is a tertiary source for grades 6–12}} A motion on September 27, 1991, to give the nomination a favorable recommendation failed 7–7, and the Judiciary Committee voted 13–1 to send it to the full Senate without recommendation.{{Sfn|Herman|Friedman|Israel|2013|p=389}}<ref>{{cite news| title=Judiciary Committee Votes On Recent Supreme Court Nominees| agency=Compiled by the Senate Library| url=https://www.judiciary.senate.gov/nominations/supreme-court/committee-votes| publisher=Senate Committee on the Judiciary| location=Washington, D.C.| access-date=June 5, 2019| archive-date=June 5, 2019| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190605225044/https://www.judiciary.senate.gov/nominations/supreme-court/committee-votes| url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="CRS-R44234"/> 

=== Anita Hill accusations ===

{{external media|video1=[https://www.c-span.org/video/?c5079445/user-clip-clarence-thomas-opening-statement Clarence Thomas Opening Statement<br />October 11, 1991], [[C-SPAN]]|float=right|video2=[https://www.c-span.org/video/?c4981323/anita-hill-opening Anita Hill Opening Statement<br />October 11, 1991], [[C-SPAN]]|video3=[https://www.c-span.org/video/?21974-1/thomas-hearing-day-1-part-1&event=21974&playEvent Thomas Second Hearing Day 1, Part 1<br />October 11, 1991], [[C-SPAN]]|video4=[https://www.c-span.org/video/?22097-1/thomas-hearing-day-1-part-2 Thomas Second Hearing Day 1, Part 2<br />October 11, 1991], [[C-SPAN]]|}}

At the conclusion of the committee's confirmation hearings, the Senate was debating whether to give final approval to Thomas's nomination. An [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] interview with [[Anita Hill]], a former colleague of Thomas at the EEOC, was soon leaked to the press and allegations of sexual harassment followed.{{Sfn|Cox|2008|p=71–72}}{{Sfn|Zeppos|Hall|1992|p=870–871}} As a result, on October 8, the final vote was postponed, and the confirmation hearings were reopened. It was only the third time in the Senate's history that such an action was taken and the first since 1925, when Justice [[Harlan F. Stone]]'s nomination was recommitted to the Judiciary Committee.<ref name="CRS-R44234" />

Hill was raised in [[Oklahoma]] and, like Thomas, graduated from Yale Law School.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Bouchard |first1=Mikayla |last2=Taylor |first2=Marisa Schwartz |date=2018-09-27 |title=Flashback: The Anita Hill Hearings Compared to Today |language=en-US |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/27/us/politics/anita-hill-kavanaugh-hearings.html |access-date=2023-07-26 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> She told James Brudney, a fellow Yale alumnus, about alleged sexual advances Thomas had made, telling him that she also did not wish to testify or make the allegations public to the Senate Judiciary Committee. Hill requested to the staff of Senator [[Joe Biden]], the chair of the committee, that her allegations be made anonymously if she chose to testify and that Thomas not be informed of them, which Biden declined. Hill then notified Democratic staffers the day after the hearings had ended that she wished to make her allegations known to the committee.{{Sfn|Foskett|2004|p=229–230, 232}}[[File:Anita_Hill_testifying_in_front_of_the_Senate_Judiciary_Committee_(cropped).jpg|thumb|Hill testifying during the second confirmation hearings|260x260px]]Hill's allegations were corroborated by Susan Hoerchner, a judge in California, who also wished to remain anonymous.{{sfn|Mayer|Abramson|1994|p=238}}{{Sfn|Foskett|2004|p=230–231}} Hoerchner called Harriet Grant, a chief counsel to Biden, to inform him of her allegations. She recalled that Thomas told Hill in an elevator at the EEOC that he would ruin her career if she spoke about his behavior.{{sfn|Mayer|Abramson|1994|p=235, 238}} When Grant told Hill and Hoerchner that the FBI would be involved, they were reluctant to be investigated. Hill declined to speak with the FBI, as she feared it would misconstrue her words, so instead arranged to deliver a written statement. The statement described how Thomas pressured her to date him, and included descriptions of him speaking about sexual interests involving pornographic films.{{sfn|Mayer|Abramson|1994|p=241–243}} Hill also alleged that Thomas spoke of sex at work despite her being uncomfortable with the subject, adding, "I sensed that my discomfort with his discussions only urged him on, as though my reaction of feeling ill at ease and vulnerable was what he wanted".{{Sfn|Foskett|2004|p=233}} The FBI report of its investigation was not made public. The White House announced that the FBI had found the allegations "without foundation". Congressional officials who had seen the report told the ''New York Times'' that "the bureau could not draw any conclusion because of the 'he said, she said' nature of the subject".<ref>{{cite news |last=Lewis |first=Neil A. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/10/07/us/law-professor-accuses-thomas-of-sexual-harassment-in-1980-s.html |title=Law Professor Accuses Thomas Of Sexual Harassment in 1980's |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=October 7, 1991 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230628193441/https://www.nytimes.com/1991/10/07/us/law-professor-accuses-thomas-of-sexual-harassment-in-1980-s.html |archive-date=June 28, 2023 |access-date=November 19, 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Selk |first=Avi |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2018/10/02/fbis-anita-hill-investigation-quick-professional-flawed/ |title=How the FBI's flawed investigation of Clarence Thomas became a model for Kavanaugh's |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=October 2, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230623184211/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2018/10/02/fbis-anita-hill-investigation-quick-professional-flawed/ |archive-date=June 23, 2023 |access-date=November 19, 2023}}</ref> The use of the FBI was contentious in the Judiciary Committee because it answers to the president, who was sponsoring Thomas. Biden used the FBI instead of the committee's investigators to avoid the appearance of partisanship.{{sfn|Mayer|Abramson|1994|p=241}}

==== Second hearing ====
The hearings reconvened on October 11, 1991, with Thomas going first. In his opening statement, he denied that he had said or done anything to Hill "that could have been mistaken for sexual harassment". He told the Committee that he would not allow any questions about "what goes on in the most intimate parts of my private life or the sanctity of my bedroom" so as not to "provide the rope for my own lynching".{{sfn|Mayer|Abramson|1994|p=289–290}} 

The committee then questioned Hill for seven hours. She testified that ten years earlier Thomas had subjected her to comments of a sexual nature, calling it "behavior that is unbefitting an individual who will be a member of the Court".{{sfn|Mayer|Abramson|1994|p=292–295}}<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1991/10/12/us/the-thomas-nomination-excerpts-from-senate-s-hearings-on-the-thomas-nomination.html "The Thomas Nomination; Excerpts From Senate's Hearings on the Thomas Nomination"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170316191918/http://www.nytimes.com/1991/10/12/us/the-thomas-nomination-excerpts-from-senate-s-hearings-on-the-thomas-nomination.html |date=March 16, 2017 }}, ''[[The New York Times]]'' (1991-10-12):<br />"Q: Professor Hill, there's a big difference between your articulating your version of events, contrasted with your statement that Judge Thomas sexually harassed you. And in the transcript of your October 7 interview, you responded to a question saying that it was sexual harassment.<br />
"A: In my opinion, based on my reading of the law, yes, it was. But later on, immediately following that response, I noted to the press that I did not raise a claim of sexual harassment in this complaint. It seems to me that the behavior has to be evaluated on its own with regard to the fitness of this individual to act as an Associate Justice. It seems to me that even if it does not rise to the level of sexual harassment, it is behavior that is unbefitting an individual who will be a member of the Court."</ref><ref>[[Katha Pollitt|Pollitt, Katha]]. ''Subject to Debate: Sense and Dissents on Women, Politics, and Culture'', page 161 (2001): "The question Hill's testimony placed before us was not whether Thomas was guilty of a legally actionable offense (she herself was unsure if his behavior added up to sexual harassment) but whether he belonged on the Supreme Court."</ref> Her testimony included graphic details, and some senators questioned her aggressively.<ref>{{cite web|first=Grace|last=Segers|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/here-are-some-of-the-questions-anita-hill-fielded-in-1991/|title=Here are some of the questions Anita Hill answered in 1991|publisher=[[CBS News]] |location=New York City|date=September 19, 2018|access-date=October 13, 2020|archive-date=October 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201019234131/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/here-are-some-of-the-questions-anita-hill-fielded-in-1991/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Julia|last=Jacobs|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/20/us/politics/anita-hill-testimony-clarence-thomas.html|title=Anita Hill's Testimony and Other Key Moments From the Clarence Thomas Hearings|newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 20, 2018|access-date=October 13, 2020|archive-date=November 25, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181125124653/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/20/us/politics/anita-hill-testimony-clarence-thomas.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Hill accused Thomas of making two sexually offensive remarks to her: comparing his penis to that of [[Long Dong Silver]], a black porn star, and saying he had discovered a pubic hair on his [[Coca-Cola]] can.<ref name=":7">{{cite book |last=Fiske |first=John |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qWXDcHQ9GwkC&q=%22will%20not%20get%20into%20any%20discussions%20that%20I%20might%20have%20had%20about%20my%20personal%20life%22&pg=PA113 |title=Media matters: race and gender in U.S. politics |publisher=University of Minnesota Press |year=1998 |isbn=0-8166-2463-1 |edition=Third printing, revised |location=Minneapolis, Minnesota |pages=82, 113 |access-date=October 25, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200729131328/https://books.google.com/books?id=qWXDcHQ9GwkC&pg=PA113&q=%22will%20not%20get%20into%20any%20discussions%20that%20I%20might%20have%20had%20about%20my%20personal%20life%22 |archive-date=July 29, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>{{sfn|Foskett|2004|p=245–246}}

{{Quotebox
| quote = And from my standpoint as a black American, as far as I'm concerned, [this proceeding] is a high-tech [[lynching]] for uppity blacks that in any way deign to think for themselves, to do for themselves, to have different ideas, and it is a message that unless you kowtow to the old order, this is what will happen to you. You will be lynched, destroyed, caricatured by a committee of the United States Senate rather than hung from a tree.
| source = Thomas, testifying as part of his opening statement before the [[Senate Judiciary Committee]]<ref>{{Cite news |title=JUDGE THOMAS'S EVENING STATEMENT TO THE COMMITTEE |language=en-US |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1991/10/12/judge-thomass-evening-statement-to-the-committee/9c96485a-bc34-4815-9478-ff1883317382/ |access-date=2023-07-26 |issn=0190-8286}}</ref>
| width = 30%
}}

In the evening, Thomas was recalled before the committee. He again denied the allegations and was prompted by Senator [[Orrin Hatch]]'s questioning to launch a speech that criticized the proceeding as a "high-tech lynching for uppity blacks".{{sfn|Mayer|Abramson|1994|p=298–299}} The speech resonated with Southern blacks and stimulated Thomas's supporters,{{sfn|Foskett|2004|p=248}} with public opinion shifting in his favor afterward.{{sfn|Mayer|Abramson|1994|p=300}}{{Sfn|Herman|Friedman|Israel|2013|p=391}}  

Hill was the only person to publicly testify that Thomas had sexually harassed her.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/10/15/us/the-thomas-nomination-excerpts-from-an-interview-with-another-thomas-accuser.html|title=The Thomas Nomination; Excerpts From an Interview With Another Thomas Accuser|newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=October 15, 1991|access-date=February 15, 2017|archive-date=February 5, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210205194858/https://www.nytimes.com/1991/10/15/us/the-thomas-nomination-excerpts-from-an-interview-with-another-thomas-accuser.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Angela Wright, who worked under Thomas at the EEOC and had alleged that "Thomas had continually pressured her to date him and made sexual comments about women's bodies",<ref name="key">{{cite news |last=Jacobs |first=Julia |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/20/us/politics/anita-hill-testimony-clarence-thomas.html |title=Anita Hill's Testimony and Other Key Moments From the Clarence Thomas Hearings |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 20, 2018 |access-date=April 16, 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/10/13/us/the-thomas-nomination-on-the-hearing-schedule-eight-further-witnesses.html|title=The Thomas Nomination; On the Hearing Schedule: Eight Further Witnesses|newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=October 13, 1991|access-date=April 16, 2023|archive-date=July 29, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180729051651/https://www.nytimes.com/1991/10/13/us/the-thomas-nomination-on-the-hearing-schedule-eight-further-witnesses.html|url-status=live}}</ref> and a corroborating witness she had named were not called to testify.<ref name="key" /> Their written depositions were entered into the congressional records unrebutted.{{sfn|Mayer|Abramson|1994|p=344}}{{Sfn|Viera|Gross|1998|p=219}}<ref name="nytimes excerpts">{{cite news|title=The Thomas Nomination; Excerpts From Judiciary Committee's Interview of Angela Wright|work=[[The New York Times]] |date=October 4, 1991|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/10/14/us/thomas-nomination-excerpts-judiciary-committee-s-interview-angela-wright.html|access-date=November 1, 2011|archive-date=November 10, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110115421/http://www.nytimes.com/1991/10/14/us/thomas-nomination-excerpts-judiciary-committee-s-interview-angela-wright.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Sukari Hardnett, a former Thomas assistant, wrote to the Senate committee that although Thomas had not harassed her, "If you were young, black, female and reasonably attractive, you knew full well you were being inspected and auditioned as a female."<ref>{{cite news|first=Ruth|last=Marcus|author-link=Ruth Marcus (journalist)|date=October 30, 2007|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/10/02/AR2007100201822.html|title=One Angry Man, Clarence Thomas Is No Victim|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=August 25, 2017|archive-date=November 8, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101108064434/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/10/02/AR2007100201822.html|url-status=live}}</ref>{{sfn|Mayer|Abramson|1994|p=134}}

In addition to Hill and Thomas, the committee heard other witnesses.<ref name="CRS-R44234">{{cite web| last=McMillion| first=Barry J.| title=Supreme Court Appointment Process: Senate Debate and Confirmation Vote| date=September 7, 2018| series=CRS Report (R44234)| url=https://fas.org/sgp/crs/misc/R44234.pdf| publisher=Congressional Research Service| location=Washington, D.C.| access-date=June 14, 2019| archive-date=November 23, 2020| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201123141657/https://fas.org/sgp/crs/misc/R44234.pdf| url-status=live|pages=22–23}} </ref> A former colleague, Nancy Altman, testified that for two years she had shared an office with Thomas at the Department of Education and "heard virtually every conversation" Thomas had and never heard him make a sexist or offensive comment.<ref>"Nomination of Judge Clarence Thomas to be Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States", Senate Hearing 102–1084, pt. 4, [http://www.gpoaccess.gov/congress/senate/judiciary/sh102-1084pt4/589-590.pdf p. 590] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100708141543/http://www.gpoaccess.gov/congress/senate/judiciary/sh102-1084pt4/589-590.pdf |date=July 8, 2010 }}</ref>{{Primary source inline|plural=yes|date=November 2023}} 

On October 13, Hill voluntarily took and passed a polygraph test, which her lawyer took as proof that she had been truthful about the harassment claims, even if the test was not admissible as evidence in court. Danforth's office then issued a statement saying that persons suffering from a delusional disorder might pass a lie detector test.<ref>{{cite news |last=Clymer |first=Adam |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/10/14/us/thomas-nomination-parade-witnesses-support-hill-s-story-thomas-s-integrity.html |title=Parade of Witnesses Support Hill's Story, Thomas's Integrity |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=October 14, 1991 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140325215754/http://www.nytimes.com/1991/10/14/us/thomas-nomination-parade-witnesses-support-hill-s-story-thomas-s-integrity.html |archive-date=March 25, 2014 |access-date=November 25, 2023}}</ref><ref name="Jacobs 2018 q975">{{cite web | last=Jacobs | first=Julia | title=Anita Hill's Testimony and Other Key Moments From the Clarence Thomas Hearings | website=The New York Times | date=2018-09-20 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/20/us/politics/anita-hill-testimony-clarence-thomas.html | access-date=2023-11-29}}</ref><ref name="Totenberg 2018 t483">{{cite web | last=Totenberg | first=Nina | title=Kavanaugh Allegations Recall 1991's Supreme Court Scandal, With Key Differences | website=NPR | date=2018-09-17 | url=https://www.npr.org/2018/09/17/648783307/from-anita-hill-to-christine-blasey-ford-the-similarities-and-differences | access-date=2023-11-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Mencimer |first1=Stephanie |title=Republicans Had 27 Years to Prepare for Another Anita Hill Moment. They're Still Blowing It. |url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2018/09/republicans-had-27-years-to-prepare-for-another-anita-hill-moment-theyre-still-blowing-it/ |website=Mother Jones |access-date=29 November 2023 |date=21 September 2018}}</ref> After the confirmation hearings ended, they became a focus of divided scholarship, with authors who revisited them reaching varying conclusions in favor of either Thomas or Hill.{{Sfn|Herman|Friedman|Israel|2013|p=391}} 

=== Senate votes ===
[[File:Virginia Thomas.JPG|thumb|Thomas was sworn in as a member of the U.S. Supreme Court by Justice [[Byron White]] on October 23, 1991. His wife, [[Virginia Thomas]], looks on in the foreground.]]On October 15, 1991, the Senate voted to confirm Thomas as an [[Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States|associate justice]], 52–48.<ref name="CRS-R44234" /> Thomas received the votes of 41 Republicans and 11 Democrats, while 46 Democrats and two Republicans voted to reject his nomination.<ref name="NYT19911016">{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/10/16/us/the-thomas-confirmation-how-the-senators-voted-on-thomas.html| title=The Thomas Confirmation; How the Senators Voted on Thomas| author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->| agency=[[Associated Press]]| date=October 16, 1991| work=[[The New York Times]]| location=New York City| access-date=June 5, 2019| archive-date=June 5, 2019| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190605225044/https://www.nytimes.com/1991/10/16/us/the-thomas-confirmation-how-the-senators-voted-on-thomas.html| url-status=live}}</ref>

The 99 days during which Thomas's nomination was pending in the Senate was the second-longest of the 16 nominees receiving a final vote since 1975, second only to Bork's 108 days.<ref name="CRS-R44234" /> The vote to confirm Thomas was the narrowest margin for approval in more than 100 years.{{Sfn|Zeppos|Hall|1992|p=871}}

Thomas received his [[commission (document)|commission]] on October 23 and took the prescribed constitutional and judicial oaths of office, becoming the Court's [[List of justices of the Supreme Court of the United States|106th justice]].{{Sfn|Zeppos|Hall|1992|p=870}}{{Refn|Thomas was 43 years old when he was appointed to the Supreme Court.{{sfn|Rossum|2013|p=221}}|group=lower-alpha}} He was sworn in by Justice [[Byron White]] in a ceremony initially scheduled for October 21, which was postponed because of the death of Chief Justice [[William Rehnquist]]'s wife, Natalie.<ref>{{cite news |author=Dowd |first=Maureen |date=October 19, 1991 |title=The Thomas Swearing-In; A Festive Mood at Thomas Swearing-In |work=[[The New York Times]] |agency=[[Associated Press]] |location=New York City |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/10/19/us/the-thomas-swearing-in-a-festive-mood-at-thomas-swearing-in.html?sec=&spon= |url-status=live |access-date=February 15, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210112050841/https://www.nytimes.com/1991/10/19/us/the-thomas-swearing-in-a-festive-mood-at-thomas-swearing-in.html?sec=&spon= |archive-date=January 12, 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| last=Greenhouse| first=Linda| author-link=Linda Greenhouse| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/10/24/us/thomas-sworn-in-as-106th-justice.html| title=Thomas Sworn in as 106th Justice| work=[[The New York Times]]| location=New York City| date=October 24, 1991| access-date=February 15, 2017| archive-date=November 12, 2020| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201112024032/https://www.nytimes.com/1991/10/24/us/thomas-sworn-in-as-106th-justice.html| url-status=live}}</ref>{{Sfn|Greenburg|2007|p=111}} His first set of law clerks included future judges [[Gregory G. Katsas|Gregory Katsas]] and [[Gregory E. Maggs|Gregory Maggs]] and U.S. Ambassador [[Christopher Landau]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Interview with Christopher Landau |url=https://www.maxraskin.com/interviews/christopher-landau |access-date=2023-04-18 |website=Interviews with Max Raskin |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2021-08-30 |title=Justice Thomas Joins the Supreme Court – The Honorable Gregory G. Katsas |url=https://www.harvard-jlpp.com/justice-thomas-joins-the-supreme-court/ |access-date=2023-04-18 |website=Harvard Journal of Law & Public Policy |language=en-US}}</ref>
